Big O Notation

Big O notation measures how fast an algorithm runs as input size increases.

Linear Search
-> Best case: O(1) (found at first position)
-> Average case: O(n/2) → O(n)
-> Worst case: O(n) (element at end or not found)

>Checks each element one by one.

Binary Search
-> Best case: O(1) (middle element)
-> Average case: O(log n)
-> Worst case: O(log n)

>Works only on sorted arrays and eliminates half search space each step.

Binary Search is better for Ecommerce because:

-> E-commerce has huge product data
-> Searching must be fast
-> Data can be sorted by name / ID
-> O(log n) is much faster than O(n)